s in the Sea traces the development of Nascimento’s thought across the decades of her activism and writing, covering topics such as the Black woman, race and Brazilian society, Black freedom, and Black aesthetics and spirituality. Incisive introductory and analytical essays provide key insights into the political and historical context of Nascimento’s work. This engaging collection includes an essay by Bethânia Gomes, Nascimento’s only daughter, who shares illuminating and uniquely personal insights into her mother’s life and career.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Jun 2024) 0aBlack peoplexRace identityzBrazil2DLC. 0aBlack peoplexRace identityzBrazil. 0aBlack peoplezBrazilxSocial conditionsy20th century2DLC. 0aBlack peoplezBrazilxSocial conditionsy20th century. 0aSocial movementszBrazilxHistoryy20th century2DLC. 0aSocial movementszBrazilxHistoryy20th century. 0aWomen intellectualszBrazilvBiography2DLC. 0aWomen intellectualszBrazilvBiography. 0aWomen, BlackzBrazilxSocial conditionsy20th century2DLC. 0aWomen, BlackzBrazilxSocial conditionsy20th century. 7aHISTORY / Latin America / South America.2bisacsh  aArchie Davies.  aBeatriz Nascimento.  aBethania Gomes.  aBlack history.  aBlack studies.  aBlack.  aBlackness.  aBrazil.  aBrazilian history.  aChristen A. Smith.  aThe Dialectic Is in the Sea: The Black Radical Thought of Beatriz Nascimento.  aWomen's History month.  afeminism.  afeminist leaders.  afeminist.  aquilombo.  awomen's history.  awomens studies.1 aDavies, Archie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDavies, Archie, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aGomes, Bethânia N. F., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGomes, Bethânia N. F., eeditor.4ed